    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>China and Cuba</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Esther B Siegel letter on giving permanent trade benefits to China despite human rights violations; suggests extending similar recognition to Cuba (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You report that the Senate voted overwhelmingly to give permanent trade benefits to China ''despite the State Department's recent conclusion that China's human rights violations have, if anything, grown more egregious this year'' (front page, Sept. 20). Isn't it time we recognized Cuba, a small nation with which we could trade, and perhaps improve the lives of people there, or don't we have the courage?</p>
        <p>ESTHER B. SIEGEL  Southampton, N.Y., Sept. 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You report that the Senate voted overwhelmingly to give permanent trade benefits to China ''despite the State Department's recent conclusion that China's human rights violations have, if anything, grown more egregious this year'' (front page, Sept. 20). Isn't it time we recognized Cuba, a small nation with which we could trade, and perhaps improve the lives of people there, or don't we have the courage?</p>
        <p>ESTHER B. SIEGEL  Southampton, N.Y., Sept. 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
